), which was usually spelt <i>Hull</i> or <i>Hulle</i> during the Middle Ages. <i>Hull</i> with this origin was also once the name of two other places, now lost, one in Great Budworth (Cheshire), and the other in Inkpen (Berkshire). See also   Hell  .","English: perhaps a habitational name from Kingston upon Hull in East Yorkshire, which takes its name from the river Hull (perhaps related to Danish <i>hul</i> ‘hole, hollow’, or perhaps a British name based on the root <i>seul-</i> ‘mud’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Huller","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived on a hill, from Middle English <i>huller</i> (see   Hull  ). This type of topographic name formation with <i>-er</i>, equivalent to <i>atte Hull</i>, is common in southern England and absent from northern England. See   Hiller   and   Heller  .","English: in Yorkshire, a late variant of   Hulley  .","English: variant of   Hillier   from Middle English <i>huller</i> ‘roofer’, found in Western and southern England as far east as Sussex."]},{"name":"Hugh","meanings":["English, Welsh, and Scottish (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Hue</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Hugo</i> (ultimately derived from <i>hugi-</i> ‘mind, spirit’). This was a very popular name in England after the Norman Conquest, partly due to the reputation of Saint Hugh of Lincoln (1140–1200), who was born in Burgundy and who established the first Carthusian monastery in England.","Scottish and Irish: adopted as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Aodh</i>, a derivative of a Gaelic word meaning ‘fire’. See   Hughes  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 邱 and 丘, based on their Hakka pronunciation; see   Qiu   1 and 2."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Ralph Hull was born in 1279, in Pulham, Dorset, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Sir Ralph Hull. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1279–":"1279–Surnud","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1279–Female":"1279–Surnud","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","1280":"1280","Pulham, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Pulham, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England"},"fi":{"1279–":"1279–Kuollut","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1279–Female":"1279–Kuollut","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","1280":"1280","Pulham, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Pulham, Dorset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England"},"fr":{"1279–":"1279–Décédée","1280–Male":"1280–Décédé","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","1279–Female":"1279–Décédée","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","1280":"1280","Pulham, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Pulham, Dorset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Dorset, England":"Dorset, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Ralph Hull est née en 1279, à Pulham, Dorset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Sir Ralph Hull. Elle est décédée dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1279–":"1279–Verstorben","1280–Male":"1280–Verstorben","1300–Male":"1300–Verstorben","1279–Female":"1279–Verstorben","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","1280":"1280","Pulham, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Pulham, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Ralph Hull wurde 1279 in Pulham, Dorset, England, United Kingdom geboren. Sie hatte mit Sir Ralph Hull mindestens 